    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>If you have the lines from the file already in a string, you could do this:</p>\n\n<pre><code>int len = txt.split(System.getProperty(\"line.separator\")).length;\n</code></pre>\n\n<p><strong>EDIT:</strong></p>\n\n<p>Just in case you ever need to read the contents from a file (I know you said you didn't, but this is for future reference), I recommend using <a href=\"http://commons.apache.org/\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Apache Commons</a> to read the file contents into a string. It's a great library and has many other useful methods. Here's a simple example:</p>\n\n<pre><code>import org.apache.commons.io.FileUtils;\n\nint getNumLinesInFile(File file) {\n\n    String content = FileUtils.readFileToString(file);\n    return content.split(System.getProperty(\"line.separator\")).length;\n}\n</code></pre>\n"
